Can we anticipate a structural change in consumption throughout the year and maybe beyond? Say 50%. Will storage capacity be maxed out? Probably. The price war’s onset sent the oil markets careening into a high degree of volatility, but future prices should rise back to a more normal level once the current set of negotiation disagreements are resolved and Trump’s brokered truce between SA and Russia moves forward. If Putin’s short-term goal was to decimate American competitors, he achieved it; however, shale drilling (due to a front-end spike in initial production curves and high fixed costs) is typically dormant in an adverse price environment and can be quickly ramped up again once prices rise. American producers won’t stay down for long, and should soon be able to introduce more competitiveness to the market that will drive prices closer towards equilibrium. It’s merely a question of how much progress can be made before mid-May.
